{{Infobox legislation |short_title = Indemnity Act, 1961 |legislature = |image = Coat of Arms of South Africa (1932-2000).svg |imagesize = |imagealt = |caption = |long_title = Act to indemnify the Government, its officers and all other persons acting under its or their authority in respect of acts, announcements, statements or information advised, commanded, ordered, directed, done, made or published in good faith for the prevention or suppression of internal disorder or the maintenance or restoration of good order or public safety or essential services or the preservation of life or property in any part of South Africa included in the Republic or the termination of a state of emergency in certain areas included in the Republic, and to provide for matters incidental thereto. |citation = Act No. 61 of 1961 |territorial_extent = |enacted_by = [[Parliament of South Africa]] |date_enacted = |date_passed = |enacted_by2 = |date_enacted2 = |date_passed2 = |date_assented = 28 June 1961 |royal_assent = |date_signed = |date_commenced = 5 July 1961 |date_of_expiry = |date_repealed = |administered_by = |bill = |bill_citation = |bill_date = |introduced_by = |1st_reading = |2nd_reading = |3rd_reading = |conf_committee_passed = |bill2 = |bill_citation2 = |bill_date2 = |introduced_by2 = |1st_reading2 = |2nd_reading2 = |3rd_reading2 = |conf_committee_passed2 = |date_conf_committee = |white_paper = |committee_report = |amendments = |repeals = |related_legislation = |summary = |keywords = |status = spent }} The '''Indemnity Act 61 of 1961''' was a law enacted by the [[apartheid]] government in [[South Africa]], which protected the government from any legal repercussions of the [[Sharpeville massacre]] and other violent events that followed. It prevented the courts from hearing any criminal charges or civil claims against the government, its leaders or its employees for actions taken between 21 March 1960 and 5 July 1961.<ref name=salrc>{{Cite report |date=October 2011 |title=Discussion Paper 129: Project 25: Statutory Law Revision: Legislation administered by the Department of Justice and Constitutional Development |url=http://www.justice.gov.za/salrc/dpapers/dp129.pdf |publisher=[[South African Law Reform Commission]] |pages=49–50 |accessdate=3 December 2012}}</ref>
The act indemnified the [[State President of South Africa|State President]], the [[Cabinet of South Africa|Cabinet]], all members of the civil service, the [[South African Defence Force|defence force]], the [[South African Police|police force]], the [[South African Railways and Harbours|railways and harbours service]], the prison service, and anyone else acting under their direction. It applied to any actions taken, orders given or information published "in good faith" between the specified dates to protect [[public order]], essential services, life or property.<ref name=salrc /><ref>[http://www.justice.gov.za/legislation/acts/1961-061.pdf Indemnity Act 61 of 1961]</ref>
The act was precipitated by 224 civil claims for damages, amounting to approximately [[South African pound|£]]400,000 ([[South African rand|R]]800,000), served against the [[Minister of Justice (South Africa)|Minister of Justice]] in September 1960 by victims of Sharpeville and their relatives.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Sharpeville Massacre: A watershed in South Africa |first=Ambrose |last=Reeves |year=1966 |url=http://www.sahistory.org.za/topic/sharpeville-massacre-watershed-south-africa-reverend-ambrose-reeves |accessdate=3 December 2012 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121114153541/http://www.sahistory.org.za/topic/sharpeville-massacre-watershed-south-africa-reverend-ambrose-reeves |archivedate=14 November 2012 |df= }}</ref> All these claims were nullified by the act. In response to public pressure, the government set up a committee to examine the claims and to recommend ''[[ex gratia]]'' payments, but few were actually paid out.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sharpeville Massacre: World Condemnation and Political Aftermath |first=Alistair |last=Boddy-Evans |work=About.com African History |url=http://africanhistory.about.com/od/apartheid/a/SharpevilleMassacrePt3.htm |accessdate=3 December 2012}}</ref>
The act remains on the statute-books, although any claims to which it would apply would have [[period of prescription|prescribed]] (expired). It is also inconsistent with the modern [[Constitution of South Africa]], which guarantees the right of access to the courts. The [[South African Law Reform Commission]] has recommended that it should be repealed.<ref name=salrc/>
