'''''Pakenham's Case''''', Y.B. 42 Ed. III 3, pl. 14, was an old [[law of England|English]] case that held that the [[Lord of the manor|owner]] of a [[manorialism|manor]] could enforce a [[Covenant (law)|covenant]] that had been made with the previous owner of the manor. The covenant was that a [[convent]] and [[prior]] would sing in the manor chapel every week.<ref>Casner, A.J. et al. ''Cases and Text on Property, Fifth Edition.'' Aspen Publishers, New York, NY: 2004, p. 955</ref>
